edu.nyu.cs.addressbook.component

Class PhoneNumber

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.nyu.cs.addressbook.component.PhoneNumber
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Cloneable, Comparable<PhoneNumber>

    public class PhoneNumber
extends Object
implements Cloneable, Comparable<PhoneNumber>
    Author:
    shenli

    The PhoneNumber class represents phone number information.

    PhoneNumber are constant; their value could not be changed after they are created. Because PhoneNumber objects are immutable they could be shared.

        public boolean equals(Object o)

        This implementation first checks if the specified object is this PhoneNumber. If so, it returns true; if not, it checks if the specified object is a PhoneNumber object. If not, it returns false; if so, it iterates over both PhoneNumber objects, comparing corresponding fields. If any comparison returns false, this method returns false. Otherwise it returns true when the iterations complete.

      • toString

        public String toString()
        Returns the string representation of this PhoneNumber object. The string consists of fourteen characters whose format is "(XXX) YYY-ZZZZ", where XXX is the area code, YYY is the prefix, and ZZZZ is the line number. (Each of the capital letters represents a single decimal digit.)

        If any of the three parts of this phone number is too small to fill up its field, the field is padded with leading zeros. For example, if the value of the line number is 123, the last four characters of the string representation will be "0123".

        Note that there is a single space separating the closing parenthesis after the area code from the first digit of the prefix.

        Overrides:
        toString in class Object
        Returns:
        string comprising the area code, prefix, and line number

      • clone

        public PhoneNumber clone()
        Creates and returns a copy of this PhoneNumber object.

        The method clone for class PhoneNumber performs a specific cloning operation. First, if the class of this PhoneNumber object does not implement the interface Cloneable, then a CloneNotSupportedException is thrown. Note that all arrays are considered to implement the interface Cloneable. Otherwise, this method creates a new instance of the class of this PhoneNumber object and initializes all its fields with exactly the contents of the corresponding fields of this object, as if by assignment; the contents of the fields are not themselves cloned. Thus, this method performs a "shallow copy" of this object, not a "deep copy" operation.

        Overrides:
        clone in class Object
        Returns:
        a clone of this instance
        Throws:
        CloneNotSupportedException - if the object's class does not support the Cloneable interface. Subclasses that override the clone method can also throw this exception to indicate that an instance cannot be cloned.
